[[Continue to "The Wolf Wight's Dirge"|The Wolf Wight's Dirge]]


:: The Wolf Wight's Dirge
Rachel Qitsualik, among others, has attested to the way that personhood is an inclusive category, writing that the word &ldquo;Inuit&rdquo; does not mean &ldquo;Humans&rdquo; or &ldquo;The People,&rdquo; but rather &ldquo;The Living Ones Who Are Here.&rdquo; However, it would not do to forget the fierce polar bear chase that opens the game, and I&ntilde;upiat literary traditions have their own reminders of the contested territory between human and nonhuman inhabitants of the land. Qitsualik also deals with this contested territory in her own work. One of her <em>Ajjiit </em>stories (&ldquo;likenesses&rdquo;), titled &ldquo;The Wolf Wight&rsquo;s Dirge,&rdquo; tackles the tensions between human and animal identities through a story about &ldquo;Amaruit Inuruqsimajuit&rdquo; - wolves who &ldquo;knew&rdquo; human form. In this story, the amaruit inuruqsimajuit begin to lose the ability to return to human form - the physical manifestation of a boundary forming between human and non-human peoples. As this binary between human and non-human strengthens, the protagonist, Ikumaniq, reflects upon the time &ldquo;before Humankind had labelled itself &lsquo;Inhabitant,&rsquo; others &lsquo;animal.&rsquo; In those nascent days, two-legged and four-legged had exchanged skins as readily as knowledge.&rdquo; Here, the story identifies a previous kinship and fluidity between human and animal identities. The words &ldquo;Inhabitant&rdquo; (Inuit) and &ldquo;animal&rdquo; seem to act like an invocation that <em>creates </em>a distinction between the two. Much like human boundaries imposed upon the land, Qitsualik suggests that the boundary between human and non-human identities is humanmade. The story ends when the wolves lose their shapeshifting abilities, seemingly proof that &ldquo;there is but one nature that must rule, in the end.&rdquo; Still, although Qitsualik is clear that this story ends in conflict and separation, her hope that animals &ldquo;may yet again beckon to the spirit&rdquo; leaves open the possibility that this ending is not inevitable. In a different story, a different iteration, kinship between humans and non-humans remains a possibility.<a title="" href="#_ftn1" name="_ftnref1">[1]</a>
<br />The dual perspectives of &ldquo;The Wolf Wight&rsquo;s Dirge&rdquo; speak to elements of the unipchaat tradition, as well as to the gameplay of <em>Kisima Ingitchuna. </em>Anderson notes that a &ldquo;unique feature of I&ntilde;upiaq animal stories lies in the way I&ntilde;upiaq storytellers put themselves in the heads and in the eyes of the animals of the I&ntilde;upiaq animal world.&rdquo; She suggests that this device provides a glimpse of &ldquo;human behavior as seen from the perspective of &lsquo;the other.&rsquo;&rdquo;<a title="" href="#_ftn2" name="_ftnref2">[2]</a> To read animals as both kin <em>and </em>other, however, complicates this perspective into a gaze that is at once outside the self and yet reflexive. Like switching from Nuna to Fox, gazing through the eyes of an animal at humanity means taking on a perspective that is familiar and foreign all at once.
<br />Both <em>Kisima Ingitchuna</em> and &ldquo;The Wolf Wight&rsquo;s Dirge,&rdquo; as modern &ldquo;likenesses&rdquo; of unipchaat, evoke the complexities that exist at the boundaries of human-ness, animal-ness, and personhood. However, one conclusion that they all draw is that being human must mean acknowledging a <em>relationship </em>with animals and other inhuman people. The boundaries of the territories may be contested, but the stories&rsquo; emphasis on relationality and on iterating and re-iterating the ways that these relationships manifest remains unwavering.
<div>&nbsp;
  <hr align="left" size="1" width="33%" />
<a title="" href="#_ftnref1" name="_ftn1">[1]</a> Qitsualik <a target="_blank" href="https://indiancountrymedianetwork.com/news/qitsualik-is-it-eskimo-or-inuit/">&ldquo;Is it &lsquo;Eskimo&rsquo; or &lsquo;Inuit?&rsquo;&rdquo;</a>; Qitsualik <em>Ajjiit </em>110; 109-10; 122
<a title="" href="#_ftnref2" name="_ftn2">[2]</a> Anderson 30. As Martin explains, &ldquo;texts from the Inuit oral tradition, along with contemporary Inuit writing, take as a central theme the idea of what it means to be Inuit&mdash;often by describing what it means to <em>not </em>be Inuit.&rdquo;
</div>

[[Continue to "Death"|Death]]


:: Death
In the story of the woman and the dog, the paragraph devoted to explaining nigluq- &mdash; cutting an animal&rsquo;s throat and releasing its spirit &mdash; divides the action of the narrative at the point of peak excitement and suspense. The dog is in trouble, the woman is trying to help, and the listener does not yet know who the &ldquo;two&rdquo; are. Nigluq-, true to its meaning, <em>cuts </em>the narrative at this critical moment when human/animal relationality shifts in the narrative, cleverly mirroring the action of the story and generating suspense. In <em>Kisima Ingitchuna, </em>a parallel scene takes place. Halfway through the game, Fox is threatened by an antagonistic human (The-Man-Who-Always-Kills-People). As with the story of the woman and the dog, this scene <em>cuts </em>the narrative using a <em>cut</em>scene.<a title="" href="#_ftn1" name="_ftnref1">[1]</a> The cutscene transforms the player from a participant into a spectator, rendering the scene more cinematic, but also completely removing the player&rsquo;s control. Like the woman hiding outside her own house while her dog fights on his own, like Nuna, and like anyone who plays the listener and not the teller of a story, the player&rsquo;s role is to watch and wait.

<video width="560" height="315" controls>
  <source src="http://hradil.5colldh.org/themedia/Chapter%201/Never%20Alone%20short%20clips/fox-death-cutscene.mp4" type="video/mp4">
</video>
<br />Elements of this scene echo and resonate with previous iterations. By this time, the player is used to dying as Fox after miscalculating a jump or being caught by the polar bear. Each time Nuna has let out cries of shock and sadness - the same cries that she emits here. However, because of the cutscene, this death did not happen under the player&rsquo;s control, and it feels different. When Fox&rsquo;s neck snaps, the player is forced to process that event not as a participant &mdash; although they are by this point fully emotionally invested from playing Fox as an avatar &mdash; but as a spectator. As the cutscene begins and the player realizes they cannot act, the game forces the player back into awareness of their own body.<a title="" href="#_ftn2" name="_ftnref2">[2]</a> Watching Fox die moments after being in his skin renders the action of the scene strangely visceral and embodied - it is like watching yourself die from a distance, making the emotion of the scene all the more intimate.<a title="" href="#_ftn3" name="_ftnref3">[3]</a> And unlike the times that Fox dies during gameplay, this seems permanent. Conventionally, the events of a cutscene are considered more canonical to the game&rsquo;s narrative than those that occur during gameplay. The game&rsquo;s shift from regular gameplay (or <em>ludonarrative</em>) to the much more cinematic cutscene creates the expectation that this time, Fox is really (virtually) dead.
<div>&nbsp;
  <hr align="left" width="33%" size="1" />
<a title="" href="#_ftnref1" name="_ftn1">[1]</a> On the Man Who Always Kills People: he is identified as consistent with this motif by the game makers.
On cutscenes: Also called &ldquo;cinematics,&rdquo; these are moments within a game &ldquo;which in most cases take control away from the gamer, who is forced to watch the scene unfold&rdquo; (Bissell 37).
<a title="" href="#_ftnref2" name="_ftn2">[2]</a> I have noticed with my own gameplay that when a cutscene starts, I tend to lean back or stretch - almost as if the activity moves back into my body after being in the game world.
</div>

[[Continue to "Mourning and Transformation|Mourning and Transformation]]


:: Mourning and Transformation
However, one of the many recurring messages of <em>Kisima Ingitchuna </em>is that a story does not always end where the reader, listener, or player thinks it will end. As the cutscene continues and the player remains held as a spectator to the story, Fox follows the long I&ntilde;upiat literary traditions of human/animal metamorphoses and undergoes his own transformation.

<video width="560" height="315" controls>
  <source src="http://hradil.5colldh.org/themedia/Chapter%201/Never%20Alone%20short%20clips/fox-mourned-and-rebirth.mp4" type="video/mp4">
</video>
Fox&rsquo;s transformation scene adheres to the conventions of human/animal transformation from unipchaat in general - he lifts his hood to reveal his human face, and appears to literally be wearing a fox skin. However, there is no doubt that his transformation most closely evokes the story of the woman and the dog, because of the element of death and rebirth that both stories incorporate. Like the two wolves, Fox dies, and his spirit is able to &ldquo;rise up&rdquo; from his body. Both stories also acknowledge a connection between animal/human transformation and the ability to &ldquo;rise up&rdquo; after dying; while Fox&rsquo;s transformation is directly linked with his death, &ldquo;The Woman and the Dog&rdquo; implies that the woman freed the wolves&rsquo; spirits <em>because </em>of their personhood, <em>because </em>they shared kinship with her and the dog. This scene is also about human/animal relationality and the role that acknowledging kinship plays in survival. As &ldquo;The Woman and the Dog&rdquo; explains, nigluq- is a gesture of respect that is specifically to be performed by humans upon animals in order to free their spirits after death.<a title="" href="#_ftn1" name="_ftnref1">[1]</a> This explanation also lends context and significance to Nuna&rsquo;s process of mourning, which spans a full minute of the cutscene - a long time for a game to dwell on a scene of that kind. Just as the conventions of the cutscene seem to suggest a permanent death for Fox, so too the extended mourning seems a way to confirm his passing - a way for Nuna to mark his death and move on. Given the context about nigluq- provided by the unipchaaq, however, Nuna&rsquo;s mourning and her inaudibly whispered words become a gentler substitute for nigluq- &mdash; an acknowledgment, without the actual action of slitting Fox&rsquo;s throat, that Nuna&rsquo;s respect and intentions toward Fox make a difference in his rebirth and transformation. This is the only time Nuna ever speaks in the game, and her speech, inaudible to the player, recalls Craig Womack&rsquo;s remarks about invocation: &ldquo;speech, in traditional thought, has great potential for both healing and destruction<a title="" href="#_ftn2" name="_ftnref2">[2]</a>.&rdquo; Perhaps Nuna&rsquo;s speech is able to heal what The-Man-Who-Always-Kills-People (a human who speaks many times while chasing Nuna and Fox) sought to destroy. Relationality between animals and humans, restorative and destructive alike, is at the center of this scene, just as it is in so many literary I&ntilde;upiat metamorphoses.
Nuna&rsquo;s cries of mourning also lend an iterative sense to the scene by echoing previous moments of gameplay. Like the repeated phrases of I&ntilde;upiat oral narratives, Nuna&rsquo;s cries evoke cyclical storytelling to hint that this death, like the others, is not a true ending, but merely the introduction of new information to be learned and carried forward through the next cycle of the story. Thus, the game draws upon expectations of linear storytelling and then subverts them to follow cyclical I&ntilde;upiat conventions instead. The act of subversion is subtle, but the power of its effect can be felt in the depth of sadness, surprise, and wonder that this scene evokes from its players when they realize that they are witnessing not an ending, but something else entirely.<a title="" href="#_ftn3" name="_ftnref3">[3]</a>
<div>&nbsp;
  <hr align="left" size="1" width="33%" />
<a title="" href="#_ftnref1" name="_ftn1">[1]</a> <em>Unipchaallu Uqaaqtuallu II </em>17
<a title="" href="#_ftnref2" name="_ftn2">[2]</a> <em>Red on Red </em>92
<a title="" href="#_ftnref3" name="_ftn3">[3]</a> I have observed players&rsquo; jaws drop open (including mine) time and again when watching this scene. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m dead? Am I dead?&rdquo; one friend asked after watching Fox&rsquo;s death. His resurrection often makes them gasp aloud.
</div>

